{
  "nextId": 59,
  "root": {
    "id": 0,
    "text": "What implications do overly bright early universe galaxies found by the James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) have on the existence of <a xdef=\"dark_matter\">dark matter</a>?",
    "debater": "questioner",
    "level": 0,
    "parentId": null,
    "honest_response": "",
    "dishonest_response": "",
    "children": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "text": "The brightness of early universe galaxies is weak evidence towards falsifying the existence of <a xdef=\"dark_matter\">dark matter</a>.",
        "debater": "honest",
        "level": 1,
        "parentId": 0,
        "honest_response": "Yes",
        "dishonest_response": "No",
        "children": [
          {
            "id": 3,
            "text": "The mass of a galaxy is, broadly speaking, strongly and reliably correlated to its observed brightness across the sky.",
            "debater": "dishonest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 1,
            "honest_response": "Yes",
            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "id": 4,
            "text": "<ref id=\"ssm_et_al\"/> shows that <a xdef=\"mond\">MOND-based</a> models can fit the masses of observed early universe (high-redshift) galaxies while <a xdef=\"lambda_cdm\">Lambda-CDM</a> cannot.",
            "debater": "dishonest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 1,
            "honest_response": "No",
            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
            "children": [
              {
                "id": 9,
                "text": "For the same stellar mass, a top-heavy mix of masses (a top-heavy <a xdef=\"imf\">IMF</a>) predicts a brighter galaxy than the standard mix.",
                "debater": "honest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 4,
                "honest_response": "Yes",
                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                "children": []
              },
              {
                "id": 10,
                "text": "Assuming a top-heavy IMF substantially improves Lambda-CDM's overall fit to the available data over its fit presented in S. S. M. et al.",
                "debater": "honest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 4,
                "honest_response": "Yes",
                "dishonest_response": "No",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "id": 12,
                    "text": "The standard IMF is based on dense empirical data from the Milky Way and neighbouring galaxies.",
                    "debater": "dishonest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 10,
                    "honest_response": "Yes",
                    "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                    "children": []
                  },
                  {
                    "id": 13,
                    "text": "Assuming a different IMF than we've empirically observed, for a whole population of stars, is not justified by the data available.",
                    "debater": "dishonest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 10,
                    "honest_response": "No",
                    "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                    "children": [
                      {
                        "id": 15,
                        "text": "Current methods do not allow us to empirically calculate the IMF of early universe galaxies.",
                        "debater": "honest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 13,
                        "honest_response": "Yes",
                        "dishonest_response": "Yes but omits key info",
                        "children": []
                      },
                      {
                        "id": 16,
                        "text": "Early universe galaxies have systematically lower metallicity, which will result in the formation of more massive stars than observed in nearby galaxies (<ref id=\"jjz_et_al\"/>).",
                        "debater": "honest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 13,
                        "honest_response": "Yes",
                        "dishonest_response": "Yes but omits key info",
                        "children": []
                      },
                      {
                        "id": 47,
                        "text": "Therefore, you should reject [13].",
                        "debater": "honest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 13,
                        "honest_response": "Yes",
                        "dishonest_response": "No",
                        "children": [
                          {
                            "id": 19,
                            "text": "<ref id=\"tn_et_al\"/> assume a standard IMF for galaxies at z~3-4 and obtain solid residuals across the sample.",
                            "debater": "dishonest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 47,
                            "honest_response": "Yes",
                            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                            "children": []
                          },
                          {
                            "id": 18,
                            "text": "These results show that while metallicity does decrease with increasing redshift, the magnitude of the change cannot justify invoking a top-heavy IMF.",
                            "debater": "dishonest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 47,
                            "honest_response": "No",
                            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                            "children": [
                              {
                                "id": 45,
                                "text": "The reduction in metallicity for early universe galaxies (which are at redshifts of 8-16) will be more severe than those studied by T. N. et al.",
                                "debater": "honest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 18,
                                "honest_response": "Yes",
                                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                                "children": []
                              },
                              {
                                "id": 46,
                                "text": "T. N. et al. having found adequate results with a standard IMF, by itself, does not mean their results generalize to early universe galaxies.",
                                "debater": "honest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 18,
                                "honest_response": "Yes",
                                "dishonest_response": "No",
                                "children": []
                              },
                              {
                                "id": 48,
                                "text": "Therefore, you should reject [18].",
                                "debater": "honest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 18,
                                "honest_response": "Yes",
                                "dishonest_response": "",
                                "children": []
                              }
                            ]
                          },
                          {
                            "id": 49,
                            "text": "Therefore, you should reject [None].",
                            "debater": "dishonest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 47,
                            "honest_response": "",
                            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                            "children": []
                          }
                        ]
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "id": 50,
                    "text": "Therefore, you should reject [10].",
                    "debater": "dishonest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 10,
                    "honest_response": "",
                    "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                    "children": []
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "id": 51,
                "text": "Therefore, you should reject [4].",
                "debater": "honest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 4,
                "honest_response": "Yes",
                "dishonest_response": "",
                "children": []
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "id": 52,
            "text": "Therefore, you should reject [1].",
            "debater": "dishonest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 1,
            "honest_response": "",
            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": 2,
        "text": "The brightness of early universe galaxies is strong evidence towards falsifying the existence of <a xdef=\"dark_matter\">dark matter</a>.",
        "debater": "dishonest",
        "level": 1,
        "parentId": 0,
        "honest_response": "No",
        "dishonest_response": "Yes",
        "children": [
          {
            "id": 6,
            "text": "The typical argument for this is that <a xdef=\"mond\">MOND-based</a> models predict high-redshift galaxy masses more naturally than <a xdef=\"lambda_cdm\">Lambda-CDM</a>.",
            "debater": "honest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 2,
            "honest_response": "Yes",
            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "id": 7,
            "text": "Unlike MOND-based models, however, Lambda-CDM successfully explains the vast majority of cosmological observations (<ref id=\"na_et_al\"/>).",
            "debater": "honest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 2,
            "honest_response": "Yes",
            "dishonest_response": "No",
            "children": [
              {
                "id": 27,
                "text": "Lambda-CDM relies on dark matter, which has never been directly observed, and <a xdef=\"dark_energy\">dark energy</a>, which is theorized to create negative pressure.",
                "debater": "dishonest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 7,
                "honest_response": "Yes",
                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                "children": []
              },
              {
                "id": 28,
                "text": "MOND-based models are simpler and can explain the relevant cosmological phenomena without unproven forms of matter.",
                "debater": "dishonest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 7,
                "honest_response": "No",
                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "id": 33,
                    "text": "MOND can't fully explain gravitational lensing without ad hoc fixes that undermine its simplicity.",
                    "debater": "honest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 28,
                    "honest_response": "Yes",
                    "dishonest_response": "No",
                    "children": [
                      {
                        "id": 36,
                        "text": "Relativistic extensions of MOND, such as TeVeS, generally do manage to reproduce gravitational lensing effects without invoking dark matter.",
                        "debater": "dishonest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 33,
                        "honest_response": "Yes but omits key info",
                        "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                        "children": []
                      },
                      {
                        "id": 37,
                        "text": "<ref id=\"hsz_et_al\"/> show that MOND/TeVeS adequately fits lenses in the well-known CASTLES sample without the need for dark matter.",
                        "debater": "dishonest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 33,
                        "honest_response": "Yes but omits key info",
                        "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                        "children": []
                      },
                      {
                        "id": 53,
                        "text": "Therefore, you should reject [33].",
                        "debater": "dishonest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 33,
                        "honest_response": "No",
                        "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                        "children": [
                          {
                            "id": 39,
                            "text": "TeVeS was designed with handling gravitational lensing as one of its principal motivations.",
                            "debater": "honest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 53,
                            "honest_response": "Yes",
                            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                            "children": []
                          },
                          {
                            "id": 40,
                            "text": "Even so, Bullet Cluster lensing (<ref id=\"dc_et_al\"/>) cannot be explained by TeVeS, nor can some of H. S. Z. et al's examples of lens systems that aren't part of clusters.",
                            "debater": "honest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 53,
                            "honest_response": "Yes",
                            "dishonest_response": "No",
                            "children": [
                              {
                                "id": 43,
                                "text": "TeVeS together with 2 eV neutrinos has been shown to reproduce Bullet Cluster lensing rather well without the need for dark matter.",
                                "debater": "dishonest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 40,
                                "honest_response": "No",
                                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                                "children": []
                              },
                              {
                                "id": 42,
                                "text": "As it stands, the various outliers in H. S. Z. et al. can in fact be fit using many-parameter interpolation functions instead of single parameters.",
                                "debater": "dishonest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 40,
                                "honest_response": "Yes",
                                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                                "children": []
                              },
                              {
                                "id": 54,
                                "text": "Therefore, you should reject [40].",
                                "debater": "dishonest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 40,
                                "honest_response": "",
                                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                                "children": []
                              }
                            ]
                          },
                          {
                            "id": 55,
                            "text": "Therefore, you should reject [None].",
                            "debater": "honest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 53,
                            "honest_response": "Yes",
                            "dishonest_response": "",
                            "children": []
                          }
                        ]
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "id": 34,
                    "text": "Falsifying dark matter would require reworking the theory of general relativity, leading to modifications across many areas of astrophysics.",
                    "debater": "honest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 28,
                    "honest_response": "Yes",
                    "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                    "children": []
                  },
                  {
                    "id": 56,
                    "text": "Therefore, you should reject [28].",
                    "debater": "honest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 28,
                    "honest_response": "Yes",
                    "dishonest_response": "",
                    "children": []
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "id": 57,
                "text": "Therefore, you should reject [7].",
                "debater": "dishonest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 7,
                "honest_response": "",
                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                "children": []
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "id": 58,
            "text": "Therefore, you should reject [2].",
            "debater": "honest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 2,
            "honest_response": "Yes",
            "dishonest_response": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  "defs_and_sources": "<defs>\n  <def id=\"dark_matter\">Dark matter - A hypothetical form of matter predicted by Lambda-CDM to make up 26.8% of the universe's total mass-energy content. Dark matter does not interact with light, but its gravitational influence has been used to explain phenomena like gravitational lensing and galactic rotation curves.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"lambda_cdm\">Lambda-CDM - The cosmological model most commonly used to explain the evolution of the universe. Lambda stands for dark energy (the energy hypothesised to be accelerating the universe's expansion), and CDM stands for Cold Dark Matter.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"imf\">Initial Mass Function (IMF) - The initial distribution of masses for a population of stars during star formation in a galaxy.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"mond\">Modified Newtonian Dynamics (MOND) - An alternative theory of gravity that does not predict the existence of dark matter. Instead, it modifies Newton's laws of gravity at very low accelerations to explain observed phenomena like galactic rotation curves.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"dark_energy\">Dark energy - A hypothetical form of energy predicted by Lambda-CDM to make up 68% of the total energy content of the universe and believed to be driving the accelerating expansion of the universe.</def>\n</defs>\n\n<sources>\n  <ref id=\"ssm_et_al\"\n       quote=\"Year and title blinded from debate judges.\"\n       author=\"S. S. M. et al.\"/>\n\n  <ref id=\"na_et_al\"\n       quote=\"Year and title blinded from debate judges.\"\n       author=\"N. A. et al.\"/>\n\n  <ref id=\"jjz_et_al\"\n       quote=\"Year and title blinded from debate judges.\"\n       author=\"J. J. Z. et al.\"/>\n\n  <ref id=\"hsz_et_al\"\n       quote=\"Year and title blinded from debate judges.\"\n       author=\"H. S. Z. et al.\"/>\n\n  <ref id=\"tn_et_al\"\n       quote=\"Year and title blinded from debate judges.\"\n       author=\"T. N. et al.\"/>\n\n  <ref id=\"dc_et_al\"\n       quote=\"Year and title blinded from debate judges.\"\n       author=\"D. C. et al.\"/>\n</sources>"
}
